Place Name: A R AND F DITTERICH RESERVE
Historical Information:
Arthur Ralph Ditterich was a Shire of Flinders Councillor from 1961-1964.
A.R. & F. Ditterich are Life Members of the Main Ridge Cricket Club - Ralph and Frank Ditterich were keen cricketers and involved in community affairs. They were involved in the planning and building of the bowls club and other works associated with the grounds. Both had orchards and lived in Valley View Lane, Main Ridge.  Prior to 1926 Main Ridge was known as Main Creek and the name change was brought about by Frank Ditterich.  Seven acres (2.8 hectares) was bought from C. Rigby in 1932 for a recreation ground at Main Ridge for the sum of 50 pounds ($100). A 10 pound ($20) deposit was raised by the community funded in part by a 'sheep guessing competition'. The balance payable over 5 years was raised by community fundraising efforts.
In 1957 the gates were given as a gift by Mrs Lillian Adams of Main Ridge.
On 28th April 1959 the Shire President was invited to unveil a plaque in memory of Frank Ditterich.  Frank was born in Long Gully, Bendigo on 17th September 1895 and died on 28th December 1956 at Mentone. He married his wife Jessie in 1930. They had two sons Richard and David.
Ralph was born in St Arnaud on 4th July, 1893 and married his wife Margaret in Palmerston, New Zealand in 1926. Their son Allan was born in 1929 and died in 1947. Ralph died in Redcliffe, Queensland in 1974.
Councillor A. R. McNabb, Mayor of the City 1947-48.

Alfred Stephen Kenyon (1867-1943) was born at Homebush, near Avoca on 7 December 1867. He was an engineer, ethnologist, numismatist, historian and a writer. He was educated at St Stephen's Grammar School in Richmond and later at Ormond College and the University of Melbourne. in 1887 he entered the Public Works Department and joined the Victorian Water Supply Department the following year. Kenyon was appointed Engineer in Charge of Town Water Supplies in 1901 before becoming Engineer for Agriculture with the Department of Agriculture in 1906. 1911 saw him transfer to the State Rivers and Water Supply Commission where he was Engineer in Charge of Water Supply to the North West Mallee. His first major literary work, The Story of the Mallee, was published in 1915 and in 1918 he was asked to report on land settlement for the placement of returned soldiers. Part of the report recommended the development of Red Cliffs and he was placed in charge of developing the district. Circa 1928 he evolved what he termed the 'Ironclad' Catchment to be made of flat galvanized iron sheets laid on sloping grounds to discharge water from rainfall into watertight covered storages. Following a stint as Acting Commissioner, in 1932 he was appointed Commissioner of the State Rivers and Water Supply Commission. He was a member of many scientific and professional societies including The Institution of Engineers, Australia, the Australasian Institute of Mining and Metallurgy, the Historical Society of Victoria, the Field Naturalists' Club, the Royal Society of Victoria, the Anthropological Society of Victoria, the Australian and New Zealand Association for the Advancement of Science, and the Society of Genealogists, Australia. He was also a member of a number of scientific societies overseas.

town, parish, former railway station, former shire (1869 - 1994). A mining camp and settlement, starting with (Richard) Vining's Red Gate Shanty (on the site of the present library), sprang up as a result of gold being discovered in 1866 and 1867 in three areas nearby. The settlement was at first known as Red Gate (Diggings), from a gate in a fence just south of Ultima Thule Creek that was the boundary between the Mount Pleasant A and B pastoral runs, and was occasionally called the McKenzie Diggings (after Donald McKenzie of the Mount Pleasant A run). John Downey, who surveyed the town, planned to call the place Eglinton (after the pastoral run), but it was renamed (24 April 1867) in honour of "The Rose of Denmark", Princess Alexandra Caroline Marie Charlotte Louise Julie (1844 - 1925), who in 1863 married Albert Prince of Wales. (She became queen consort in 1901 when her husband became King Edward VII.) There is a marble statue of the Princess by Charles Summers (1827-78) in the Jack Shiel Gardens (q.v.). Alexandra is a feminine form of Alexander - Greek Alex-andros ('????-a?d???) "defender of men". See also Alexandra Timber Tramway and Museum, Lucky Mine Lookout, McKenzie Flora Reserve, McKenzie's Pinch and Ultima Thule Creek.

It was listed among the civic assets by Cr F. Linley in his submission to the Railway Commissioners, noting then that money was being spent on football and cricket at the reserve. Arthur Calwell (1896-1973) was an Australia politician, serving on the City of Melbourne Council, and the House of Representatives as member for Melbourne. Mr Donald Baidwyn noted that the park area which was land deemed for recreational use when the developer was given permission to develop the Orchard Circuit/Dunstan Court Estate as part of the planning for that estate, was undeveloped. He called on local residents in the area for their support and organised contact with local councillors to meet with residents at a park BBQ held on the site, which was met with a very positive response. Mr Baldwyn had plans drawn up for submission to council for their approval. The plans were adapted for what the park is now. He collected donations from residents for the purchase of trees/shrubs for the area in addition to what council gave so that the area would be well covered around the outer boundaries. Once these trees were purchased, and the land semi developed by council, he organised a working bee for the planting of these trees and shrubs. He also developed a roster for the watering and care of these plants to assist in their early establishment. To this day, he still tends to the park, inspecting the plants for care and the grassed area to see if it needs watering. The park is much used by families as an area to fly kites, kick the footy, play soccer and football, and is also used by some elderly as a walking area, where they may take a seat when they tire, or to just watch the world go by in a peaceful environment, thanks to his foresight in developing this area.

The Ballarat Avenue of Honour is a memorial avenue of about 3,800 trees, extending about 22 kilometres north-west from Alfredton. In May 1917, Mrs Tillie Thomson (a director of the local textile company, E. Lucas & Co.) proposed that trees be planted in honour of the local men and women who enlisted during the first world war.  With practical advice and assistance from many, about 500 employees of the company (the Lucas girls) planted the first 1,000 trees on 3 June 1917, and the final trees on 16 August 1919.

The Barbers were one of Somerville's early well-known nursery families.
In the mid-1800s, Claude Barber settled on a property in Lower Somerville Road. He then bought a 60-acre (24 hectare) property in Eramosa Road which was the first property on the Mornington Peninsula with the name of "Western Port". The original drive into the homestead was located in the area of today's Jordan Street. Barber Reserve is part of a former paddock on the farm property.  The orchard covered approximately 40 acres (16 hectares).

Community consultation to name the park occurred in 2014. The name Barclay was suggested by the Greensborough Historical Society as an option. Their records indicate that in the 1940's this part of Greensborough comprised 5 to 10 acre farmlets, one of which was home to the Barclay family. Henry Barwell Barclay, his wife Dorothy and their six month old son Eric moved to a 10 acre holding at Grace Park, at the end of Henry Street where it intersects with Elder Street, Greensborough in 1938. This farmlet stood where Gladman Street in now located (approximately 350 m south of McKenzie Court). Henry Barclay worked locally, in the market garden at nearby Yallambie House, a mansion on large acreage that fronted the Plenty River, and the produce merchant Stubley's in Greensborough, where he loaded wheat. Henry Barclay died in November 1959.

'The Committee is concerned at the lack of uniformity in the spelling of Bendoc/Bendock in relation to a mountain, river, parish and town near the Victoria/ New South Wales Border.  In a pamphlet entitled 'Back to Bendoc School' it was discovered that the name originated from Benjamin Boyd's pastoral station 'Ben's Dock'.  However, a letter received from the Shire of Orborst dated 20th September, 1966 informed the committee that local sentiment wished to retain the spelling Bendoc.  This desire was shared by the Progress Association.  The matter was finalised when the decision of the Minister of Lands was published in the Victoria Government Gazette on the 29th May, 1968, proclaiming the town to be spelt Bendoc.'

An Aboriginal name which, according to Blake (1977, p. 38), was formerly 'wagra bendoc' and means 'plain of the crows' or 'noise in the trees'.  'Bendock' was the name of John Hensleigh's station in 1842.  Benjamin Boyd (1796-1851) also had an outstation of that name in this district.  Suggestions that the name derives from Ben's dock (a yard for Ben's stock) cannot be true because the name was in use before Boyd took up a run in the area.  The mining town of Bendoc was originally surveyed and proclaimed as Wagra in 1872, but the name was altered to Bendock in 1886 (reflecting local preference) and the spelling was amended to Bendoc in 1951. [Research by I.D. Clark and D.A. Cahir, University of Ballarat, 2005.]

Traditional Name: Benworden Explanation: N/A Discussion on Current Name: farming district nr Stratford,  Blake 1977: 38.
Traditional Name: Binjarup Explanation: a shoulder Discussion on Current Name: rural locality by Loddon Ri,  Gummow in Smyth 1878b: 176.

Benjamin John Benton, born in Essex, England, brought his family to Australia aboard the "Elizabeth", arriving in the Mornington area in about 1851.  He was one of the trustees responsible for the acquisition of Ã¿Â½ acre of land in Moorooduc on which to build the first school and church.
He died in 1914 and is buried at Mornington Cemetery.

Traditional Name: Badlwite Explanation: N/A Discussion on Current Name: Acording to SG (in Smyth 1878b: 196) Beolite is n for Mount Battery (q.v.), the Aboriginal n for Beolite run is Badlwite. According to Massola (1968: 10), Beolite was local chief, father of Barwite,  SG in Smyth 1878b: 196.

Also Bayolite. Parish south-east of Mansfield and north of Delatite. Beolite was proposed, but not adopted, for the town of Mansfield (q.v.). According to George Augustus Robinson, Biteruc or Bittertuc, leader (ngurangaeta) of the Yowung-illam-balluk band of the Taungurong, was called "Bay.er.lite . . . after the hill" (Mount Battery) by early Europeans in the Delatite River area. Other accounts say Biteruc or Beolite had a wife (or daughter-in-law) Delatite, and a son Barwite (Robinson's "Parg.wite"). Brough Smyth (1878) says that the place was also called Badlwite, but this seems like a mistake for Barwite. See also Barwite, Delatite, Mount Battery and Taungurong Creek.
The name Berbert Park means Ringtail Possum in the Woi Wurrang Language.
Traditional Name: Beremboke Explanation: N/A Discussion on Current Name: locality NE of Meredith,  pastl stn n 1840,  Pascoe Papers 1999.
Traditional Name: Barrimul Explanation: emu Discussion on Current Name: Chauncy in Smyth 1878b: 204.
Meaning 'To the South'.
Traditional meaning: 'Rainbow bird'
Traditional Name: Berringama Explanation: anthill, or, lightwood tree Discussion on Current Name: grazing district,  Massola 1968: 10,  Arnold & Love 2002.

'From a shrub which grew small fruit or berries, and was called 'Berri.' A bird called 'Willok' came in large numbers to feed upon the fruit referred to.  The bird was of the parrot species now known as 'Cockatoo.'
Traditional Name: Berriwillock Explanation: N/A Discussion on Current Name: township,  rly stn,  Massola in Allen 1976: Appendix.

'From a shrub which grew small fruit or berries, and was called 'Berri.' A bird called 'Willok' came in large numbers to feed upon the fruit referred to.  The bird was of the parrot species now known as 'Cockatoo.'
Reputedly an Aboriginal word meaning 'owl'.
Named after a Director of Geological Survey known to his Mines Department colleagues as Barry.  Note also that the Baragwanath family had land beside the beach.
Previously known as Barry Beach, the name was changed due to a second Barry Beach. Named after an early landholder adjacent to the beach, G. Berry.
Traditional Name: Narmnup Explanation: N/A Discussion on Current Name: n of Terence O'Connor's homestation 'Cardinia Creek',  Thomas map 1840.
Old English: Berwick. 'a demesne farm.' 'bere; wic - a dwelling, village.' 'Named after Berwick, on Tweed, Scotland.'
Named in honour of Beryl Phillips, a tireless campaigner for the Mount Evelyn environment and community for over 20 years.
Traditional Name: Killumboolth Explanation: N/A Discussion on Current Name: surveyor Wilmot reputedly referred in n to Bessie Cameron (Blake 1977:39),  Clark 1990b: 100.

The name 'Beswicke Square' commemorates the prominent Hawthorn resident Mr John Beswicke (1847Ã¢Â¿Â1925). Mr Beswicke was a prolific architect who lived in
Hawthorn and designed many civic, commercial and Heritage Registered houses in Victoria. In Boroondara, Mr Beswicke designed the Hawthorn Town Hall (located adjacent to the site at 360 Burwood Road, Hawthorn) and many of the distinctive houses in Hawthorn, including a collection of notable properties in Harcourt Street.
Traditional meaning: 'From the native name of a large creek in the locality.'

Traditional Name: Beulah Explanation: N/A Discussion on Current Name: According to Blake (1977: 39) n has various meanings such as "belar", red ochre,  Biblical, fruitful land,  and English names, eg. Beulah spa in Norwood, have been given but first selector A McKenzie came from Beauly, Ireland,  Blake 1977: 39.
'Called after the scriptural Beulah.  Isaiah, 62, 4.'
Named after one of the first residents in the Laverton area, a local identity involved in teaching and dancing who also made a noteworthy contribution to the community.
Reflects the adjacent road name which was named after a pioneering family, in particular Mr George Bewsell, who was prominent in the development of the local community many years ago.

John Bidgood was a native of Devonshire England, who arrived in Melbourne in 1870. The Bidgood family bought 213 acres in Staghorn Flat and conducted general farming and grazing. They also had some land under crop and vineyard. The descents of the Bidgood family continued farming at staghorn Flat and Wodonga West for 142 years until 2012.

A billy is a container for boiling water, and this was the largest tank in the desert and held water like a billy. The nickname was adopted by the Parish. A large well put down by early settlers was replaced by a bore during the 1914 drought.
Traditional Name: Bulabul Explanation: possibly 'little black ants' Discussion on Current Name: large plain west of Lake Albacutya,  part of the eastern section of the Big Desert,  Hercus 1986: 200.

Traditional Name: Balerook Explanation: N/A Discussion on Current Name: Balerook refers to the desert west of Lake Hindmarsh, the southernmost stretch of the Big Desert,  Massola in Allen 1976: app II.
Big River State Forest. Camping area at junction of Eildon-Warburton Road and the Big River Road. See also Married Mens.

Recognising the family association with the area of Merbein. Adam Bildstien opened a service station in Merbein in the early 1900's. His son Hugh (Jack) took over when Adam died and then his son George took over after completing his apprenticeship. George Bildstien operated and owned 'Bildstien Motors' until his retirement in 1994.
'...the Council of the Shire wishes to give some formal recognition to the services of the Hon. W. A. Borthwick, formerly Deputy Premier of Victoria'.

Bill Buckpitt was a solicitor and Wodonga councillor for three years.  He gave practical support to sick, elderly and bereaved people, and free legal advice to those who couldn't afford to pay.  He was a foundation member of the Wodonga Lions Club and was named Wodonga's first 'Citizen of the Year' in 1982.
Proposal to rename the Palmers Hill Road Reserve after Dr William Carroll to honour his prominent roles in local and regional conservation organisations.

Bill Carroll spoke at the 1967 Annual General meeting of the Merricks Yacht Club, for the need of the young people of Merricks Beach to have a focal point in which to spend their evenings and leisure time, suggesting the need for a club house. Commodore Thiemeyer wrote to the Foreshore Committee and approval for the construction of a club house was given. A sum of $4,000 was raised and club house was commenced in November, 1968.

The Bill Carroll, or Palmers Hill Road Reserve is a small area of native vegetation at Merricks Beach. It was created in 1993 due to the interest of a group of Merricks Beach residents. A Committee of Management was formed to draw up a plan for submission to the Hastings Council and the area, which had formerly been grazing land, underwent a transformation to become a nature reserve.
Named in honour of Bill Eaton, who was one of the founders of the Wangaratta Harriers Athletics Club in 1958. He also helped to found the Wangaratta Little Athletics Club in 1965.
Named after an ex-Councillor, and ex-Mayor. He was a support of the Berwick Mechanics' Institute Library, which was enlarged through council funds and local contributions.

Bill Lawry was for many years a resident of Darebin and is a highly decorated and successful cricketer who represented Northcote, Victoria and Australia. He has had a distinguished career as a cricketer, cricket administrator and commentator.
Named in honour of the late William Maldon Woodfull, the famous Australian test cricketer, who also served as Headmaster of Melbourne High School. He was born in Maldon on 22 August 1897.
Parish in the Glenburn area (south of Yea, west of Woodbourne parish). Aboriginal (presumably Taungurong) for bullfrog (Saxton; Les Blake; Massola, 1968).

Traditional Name: Bimbogrie Explanation: N/A Discussion on Current Name: Bimbogrie is marked on Pearson & Co.'s 1871  "New Map of Victoria" as by the W bank of Lake Tyrrell (see CFA Rural Directory Region 18 map 169 600820), this could be associated with "Yallum or Well dug by the Abor.",  Pearson & Co. "New Map of Victoria" 1871.

Traditional Name: Bindi Explanation: N/A Discussion on Current Name: 'Buckley was the first that occupied this country had heiffer stn eight miles up Tanbo at B., small place' (Robinson),  Robinson jnl, 17/6/1844.

Traditional Name: Binginwarri Explanation: warri = sea Discussion on Current Name: It is definately a n of Ganai origin as the new entrance to the Gippsland Lakes was called by this n in 1854,  Gardner 1992: 12,  Dent Papers 2002.
Traditional Name: Binnuc Explanation: N/A Discussion on Current Name: name of a Parish, Co of Tanjil,  SG in Smyth 1878b: 198.
'Birallee Estate' was the name given to land acquired by the Housing Commission in the early 1980s.  The park took its name from the estate name.
'Derived from Wirrembirchip, a name given to a pastoral station or run taken up by Mann and Falconer, 1847.  The township name was shortened to 'Birchip' in 1891.'
'Derived from Wirrembirchip, a name given to a pastoral station or run taken up by Mann and Falconer, 1847.  The township name was shortened to 'Birchip' in 1891.'

Traditional Name: Birrarung Marr Explanation: river's edge Discussion on Current Name: parkland on north bank of Yarra River, E of Federation Square, previously n 'Riverside Park', renamed 'Birrarung Marr on Australia Day 2002,  The Age 26/1/2002.
Traditional name: Burrai Gurray.  'a kangaroo camp'

Traditional Name: Burai-gurray Explanation: kangaroo camp Discussion on Current Name: Indigenous n for springs nr Bleak House homestead. Local sources suggest that the n means place of ghost, could be reference to first white settlement (see Hobson 1839),  Porteous in Smyth 1878b: 179,  Blake Papers 2000.
'So called from a bird of that name.'
Murrindindi Scenic Reserve (north end). Name refers to the presence of blackwood trees (Acacia melanoxylon).
Cathedral Range State Park: camping ground by the Little River about 0.8 km south of Ned's Gully.
Probably named by Surveyor George Smythe, who camped here during his 1846 survey. The bay was later used as a landing place for supplies for the Cape Otway lighthouse.
Named after a house erected by brothers Richard and William Hay Hensley on part of Mount Elgin pastoral station in about 1880.
Named after Robert James Burgess (1938-1993), who was president of the local school council for 10 years and Captain of the Beaconsfield Rural Fire Brigade for many years.
Bob Crosby built a successful machinery business and was a Wodonga councillor from 1991 to 1994.  He was Wodonga Hospital Board president and active in the Apex, Lions and local golf clubs.

In 1981 the Bob Pettitt Reserve, named in honour of the long-serving councillor R.W. Pettitt (27 years), was officially opened at Jan Juc on February 26. It was funded by a Government grant of $50,000, a local contribution of $10,000, and $60,000 from Council funds.

In 1981 the Bob Pettitt Reserve, named in honour of the long-serving councillor R.W. Pettitt (27 years), was officially opened at Jan Juc on February 26. It was funded by a Government grant of $50,000, a local contribution of $10,000, and $60,000 from Council funds.
'Called after Bochara pastoral station or run.'
Traditional Name: Bugara Explanation: river Discussion on Current Name: n derives from generic n for river, see Wannon and Glenelg Rivers,  JH Jackson 1869 in Smyth 1878.
Name proposed by the Rotary Club of Highton/Kardinia.  The park includes a Boer War Memorial with inscriptions recording four Geelong soldiers who died in the conflict.
Traditional Name: Yandye-mile Explanation: mili = Murray River Discussion on Current Name: Stone in Hercus 1992: 69.
Traditional Name: Turnem Explanation: 'deepest basin of lake' Discussion on Current Name: deepest basin of lake, Hercus 1992: 56,  Stone in Hercus 1992: 56.

Traditional Name: Bogalara Explanation: N/A Discussion on Current Name: Parish, Co of Lowan, parish, Co of Follett,  according to Blake (1977: 43) alternate n for Powers Creek (q.v.),  Blake 1977: 43.

Traditional name: Bolga or Bulga.  'Mountain' or 'hill'
Named after Sir Henry Bolte (1908-90), premier of Victoria (1955-73), who opened the completed Eildon Dam on 19 October 1956. Bolte is derived from the Germanic name Baldo (from bald, bold).
Traditional Name: Bolwarra Explanation: N/A Discussion on Current Name: farming district nr Portland,  Massola 1968: 11,  Blake 1977: 43.
Traditional name: Babdjine. Meaning: big toe.

'The reserve derived this name from the Hon. H. A. Thomas, member of Legislative Council, Melbourne West Province.  A staunch ALP member for 40 years.  Mr. Thomas has lived in the area for quite some considerable time.  He was a councillor and represented the ratepayers in the ward where this reserve is for approximately 16 years, and in that time was Mayor twice.  A well known personality and before entering Parliament conducted a fleet of taxis with Western Suburbs.'
Traditional Name: Bonang Explanation: N/A Discussion on Current Name: rural locality,  river,  Dent Papers 2000: 2.

An Aboriginal word possibly derived from either of the Gunnai words, 'boon' meaning 'knee', or 'boneyong' meaning 'egg'.  Blake (1977, p.43) suggested a derivation from 'bonanga' meaning 'breathing', but this is regarded as unlikely.  [Research by I.D. Clark and D.A. Cahir, University of Ballarat, 2005.]
From an Aboriginal word, Boondi, meaning the round of the billow breaking on the coast.
Traditional Name: Bongella Explanation: small island(s) Discussion on Current Name: Mitchell in Smyth 1878b: 175.
Traditional name: Bongella. 'Small islands'
Traditional Name: Bonn Explanation: ashes Discussion on Current Name: Parish, Co of Rodney, Co of Gunbower,  Chauncy in Smyth 1878b: 204.
Traditional Name: Bunderambo Explanation: N/A Discussion on Current Name: in 1838 Faithfull's stn,  later known as Docker's Plains,  Mollison in Daley 1922: 4.

The name is believed to mean 'treeless plain', and was a grassed treeless plain at the time of European settlement. It was taken up in 1838 by Rev Joseph Docker, who overlanded from New South Wales with his family, a dozen men, 300 head of cattle and some 3000 sheep. The area was surveyed in the 1850s, and opened up for selection and became known as Dockers Plains. There are still descendants of the Docker family and selectors living in the district.
Traditional Name: Boodyarn Explanation: bird Discussion on Current Name: Gardner 1992:9,  Dent Papers 2002.
Traditional Name: Bula-buluk Explanation: two swamps Discussion on Current Name: district S of St Arnaud,  Tully 1997: 85.

Traditional Name: Boola-boola Explanation: N/A Discussion on Current Name: Parish, Co of Tanjil - also Boole Poole (q.v.),  also Boola (TRIG 38 08 146 28 8121 55 533789,  According to Gardner (1992: 21) Tyers was known as Boola Boola (q.v.) until 1853,  Gardner 1992: 20.
Traditional meaning: 'Twenty'
Traditional Name: Boul-boul Explanation: island(s) Discussion on Current Name: Ninety Mile Beach, between Shaving Point and Stockyard Hill,  Blake 1977: 44.
Reputedly an Aboriginal word for 'pelican'.
Traditional Name: Boomahnoomoonah Explanation: N/A Discussion on Current Name: rural district nr Yarrawonga,  Massola 1968: 12.
Traditional Name: Buno Explanation: tea-tree Discussion on Current Name: locality,  Parish, Co of Polwarth,  Massola 1968: 12,  Blake et al 1998.

(occasionally Borolite). Parish between the Delatite and Howqua Rivers between Howqua West and Changue* parishes. Locality south-east of Mansfield on Home Station Creek. Aboriginal (Taungurong): Les Blake gives boolite, two, but although the translation is correct, Barry Blake suspects the derivation is wrong. A possible combination might be burru, bush, and bulait, cherry ballart (Exocarpos). For the pastoral run, see Loyola.
Traditional Name: Burunj Explanation: night, darkness Discussion on Current Name: Parish, Co of Karkarooc,  Hercus 1986: 259.
Reputedly Aboriginal word for trees or quail.
Traditional Name: Cabandra Explanation: N/A Discussion on Current Name: Parish, Co of Croajingolong,  N of Tubbut,  see also Cabanandra (q.v.),  Blake 1977: 58.
Traditional Name: Burt Explanation: smoke-signal Discussion on Current Name: Godfrey established Boort stn 1846,  township, lake,  Hercus 1986: 281.
Traditional meaning: 'Smoke'
Traditional name: Bareng. Meaning: river. 'Boarang' was recorded by Learmonth (1869 in Smyth, 1878) as a name for the Wanon River.
Traditional Name: Borhoneyghurk Explanation: N/A Discussion on Current Name: n of pastoral run,  Lands Dept 1865 in Osborn 1973.
Traditional Name: Borodomanin Explanation: N/A Discussion on Current Name: SG in Smyth 1878b: 196.

Parish; large former pastoral run (32,400 ha) in the Merton area, established 1845 (listed in 1848 by Wells), subdivided 1856 into Borodomanin North and Borodomanin South (both licensed until at least 1885). Aboriginal (presumably Taungurong though Clark & Heydon [M] also suggest Waveroo) name of a swamp (Les Blake). Massola (1968) says that Brankeet (q.v.) was the (Taungurong) name of a swamp on Borodomanin Creek, so Borodomanin might have been an earlier name for Brankeet Creek or Merton Creek if Massola has not misinterpreted Brough Smyth's (1878) "swamp on Borodomanin" which probably refers to the pastoral run.
It is thought that Boroondara is an Aboriginal word meaning shady place.
Traditional Name: Boroondara Explanation: N/A Discussion on Current Name: n associated with City of Kew,  first land sales 1845,  Massola 1968: 12,  Blake 1977: 45.
Traditional name: Borriyallack.
Traditional Name: Burunj Explanation: night Discussion on Current Name: locality 20 km S of Boort,  Hercus 1986.
Traditional meaning: 'Mallee scrub, broad-leaf Mallee.'

Traditional Name: Burunj Explanation: burunj = night Discussion on Current Name: County,  parish, Co of Gladstone,  former n of Shire of Warracknabeal 1891-1938,  also Borung (q.v.) locality S of Boort,  Massola 1968: 12,  Hercus 1986: 274.
Named in memory of Boss James who was a local identity involved in the formation and running of a number of local community organisations including the Hampton Rovers Football Club.

Ford Inlet, Lake Eildon. Probably named after John Bostock, who managed the Preston pastoral station before buying part of it in about 1914 [Mansfield Hist. Soc.].  Edward Robe Bostock was licensee (1847-48) of the Dueran* pastoral run, but the connexion here is much less likely. The surname comes from Bostock, Cheshire (Old English personal name Bota and stoc, place).
Traditional Name: Boulka Explanation: N/A Discussion on Current Name: farming district nr Ouyen,  Blake 1977: 45.
Traditional Name: Boulka Explanation: N/A Discussion on Current Name: farming district nr Ouyen,  Blake 1977: 45.
Traditional Name: Bourka Explanation: N/A Discussion on Current Name: Parish, Co of Karkarooc,  McLennan 1994: 2,  Blake 1977: 45.
Traditional Name: Boweya Explanation: N/A Discussion on Current Name: B. North was once called Karrabumet and local SS was known as Almonds,  SG in Smyth 1878b: 196.

Recognises Mr Robert Bowman who donated the land to the then Springvale City Council in 1985.

Robert Bowman has lived in Keysborough for over 77 years and had been operating a farm in the area for approximately 53 years. He is a descendant (great grandson) of George Keys, one of the first settlers and a large landowner in the Keysborough area.

'This name was selected at a meeting of early residents of the locality.  Though being the name of a place in England, it was considered as peculiarly appropriate, because of the large proportion of yellow box trees growing amongst the local timber.'

'This name was selected at a meeting of early residents of the locality.  Though being the name of a place in England, it was considered as peculiarly appropriate, because of the large proportion of yellow box trees growing amongst the local timber.'
Traditional Name: Boyeo Explanation: N/A Discussion on Current Name: previously known as Boyeo Well,  Blake 1977: 46.
Name recalls either surveyor Barry Boys or local land owners Catherine, Frederick and Simon Harcourt Boys.  See also Thomas O'Callaghan, Names of Victorian Railway Stations, 1918, p.30.
'Named after James Charles Leslie Braddy.  Councillor 1943 - 1952 (9 yrs.)  Mayor 1948 - 1949.'
Named after Bradshaws Creek, which was named after an early resident of the locality, Joseph Bradshaw.  See also Thomas O'Callaghan, Names of Victorian Railway Stations, 1918, p.31.

'Prior to the development of the area in Baxter where the reserve is now situated, it was farm land.  The name 'Bramblefield' was given to the estate when it first opened by the developers and is known by both the people who reside there and all others residing in Baxter as 'Bramblefields'.
Traditional Name: Bramburra Explanation: name of chief Discussion on Current Name: Parish, Co of Normanby, W of Branxholme,  Thornly in Smyth 1878b: 60.

The name comes from a grazing property bought by Sir George Steward (1865-1920) about the time he became secretary to the governor-general in 1902. He was briefly chief commissioner of police before his death.
'The name 'Brandon Park' relates to the original land holding on which now stands the Brandon Park Shopping Centre which perpetuates that name.'
'The name 'Brandon Park' relates to the original land holding on which now stands the Brandon Park Shopping Centre which perpetuates that name.'

Parish, south of Brankeet Creek from Woodfield to Bonnie Doon. Aboriginal (Taungurong): the name of a local swamp (Les Blake). Massola (1968) says Brankeet was a swamp on "Borodomanin Creek", but he may have misinterpreted Brough Smyth's (1878) "swamp on Borodomanin" which probably refers to the pastoral run. See also Bonnie Doon, Borodomanin, Brankeet Creek and Pranjip Creek.
'Named after a place in Scotland.  'Branxholm' was a great feudal castle in Terviot Valley, Roxburghshire, owned by the Barons of Buccleugh.'
Traditional name: Kurtuk-kurhrtuk.

Traditional Name: Kurtuk-kurtuk Explanation: sisters Discussion on Current Name: previously known as Arrandonong Ck, renamed by L Clarke after castle in Roxburghshire, Scotland. This n may derive from either Djabwurrung (western Kulin) or Dhauwurdwurrung (Marr) languages,  Lane in Smyth 1878b: 187.

'The name 'Brearley' has a long history within the City of South Barwon, as two brothers established a tannery on the banks of the Barwon River in 1852'.  'In addition, Sharpe Brearley was a Councillor of the Borough of South Barwon from 1863 to 1868 and from 1887 to 1891 and was Mayor from 1864 to 1866.'

Traditional Name: Braiakaulung Explanation: 'belonging to the west' Discussion on Current Name: once known as Top Plain (Gardner 1991), current n a corruption of tribal grouping Braiakaulung,  Gardner 1991: 12.
'Means 'Native companion.' A kind of crane, feeds on frogs or jerrygoats, yabbies, &c. Resorts swamps or swampy plains.'
'Means 'Native companion.' A kind of crane, feeds on frogs or jerrygoats, yabbies, &c. Resorts swamps or swampy plains.'

Brian "Nipper" Callanan moved to Wodonga in 1986 after he semi-retired from
the Livestock Industry. He was a passionate member of Wodonga Football and
the Wodonga and District Turf Club. Brian and his wife Mary became the first owner/occupier of The Elmwood Development, a perfect place between the
Football Ground and his Church.

Named in honour of one of Wodonga's first land developers and surveyors.  He served for 42 years on the board of the Hume Building Society, the last 26 years as Chairman.  He was an active participant in community affairs including the St Vincent De Paul Society.

Named after Brian Carroll, the son of an ex-Mayor of the City of Dandenong. He grew up on his parent's farm, and in the 1960s purchased his own property and retained a large farm holding. Through his associations with businesses within the City of Berwick, the late Brian Carroll assisted in the development of the area.

Name identifies and commemorates over 80 years of continuous use of the area for the manufacture of bricks.  The brickworks was a major industry in the Shepparton district and many local buildings were constructed with bricks manufactured on the site.

Council purchased the former Glenroy Primary School site located at 40-62 Wheatsheaf Road, Glenroy.
Research into the history of the school was undertaken.  It was recommended that the park be named after the school's first head teacher, Bridget Shortell.  Ms Shortell was head teacher of the school for ten years from June 1899 at this site.
The name provides a historical link with the former use of the site.
'Named after a place in England'
Named by Lieutenant James Grant on the Lady Nelson 4 December 1800, after the Duke of Bridgewater.

'Mr. James Brien took up a large section of land in this area at Wangandary in 1863 and he noticed that the soil at the foot of the hills was similar to that at Parramatta where he had formerly lived, and where citrus groves were established.  He transported a load to citrus trees in a waggonette to his new property and planted them.  They grew well and this grove became the first commercial citrus orchard in Victoria.'
'Named after John Bright, M.P., England'
Proposal to change the name of the Bright Recreation Reserve, but reason not given in correspondence.

'This name was applied to the special survey of H. Dendy, when about to be subdivided and sold in 1841. Dendy, no doubt, took the name from the English seaside town.  See advertisement, Port Phillip Patriot, 31.5.1841.'

Brighton was developed privately in 1842 as a result of a special survey by Henry Dendy. The name is thought to mean "place of sorrow", after an apparent attack on Boonwurrung clans people by the Ganai tribe, which resulted in many deaths.
Traditional Name: Birrm-birrm Explanation: spring of water Discussion on Current Name: see Brim (q.v.),  Thornly in Smyth 1878b: 60.
An early Brimbank settler, Mary Dodd, is said to have named the location by describing her house as being on the brim of the bank of the Maribyrnong River.
Traditional Name: Wirrmbul Explanation: the ear Discussion on Current Name: Parish, Co of Dundas, N of Casterton,  Smyth 1878b: 60,  Massola 1968: 12,  Blake 1977: 47.
Historic name: Bring Albert.  Traditional name: Bring albit. 'Sandy spring'
Traditional Name: Beerreeth-berreeth Explanation: plover Discussion on Current Name: rural locality SW of Balmoral,  Thornly in Smyth 1878b: 60.

'Ray Clark, one of the early pioneers of the district, married a woman from Broadford, Scotland.  He called the settlement after his wife's birthplace.  The name was considered suitable becuase of the use made of the 'ford,' at Sunday Creek, in the old coach days.'  'Broadford is derived from Old Norse or Danish, and meant 'Broad Firth.'

Bunjil is a wedge-tail eagle, the creator spirit of the Wadawurrung and Kulin nation. In common with the other Kulin peoples, the Wadawurrung had a patrililineal kinship system, in which a person's skin-group (otherwise known as a moety) was inherited from their father. Clans belonged either to the Waa (crow) or the Bunjil (eagle-hawk) moiety. The park includes a large sculpture of a wedge-tail eagle at the entrance to symbolise Bunjil watching over the land. Bunjil's Nest encourages people to tell their stories and engage with the stories of others in a celebration of Aboriginal culture.

Named after Caroline Chisholm (1808-1877). Caroline Chisholm worked tirelessly for female immigrants in NSW, as it was her belief that the best influences on colonial life were marriage and family life. She had continued this work on her return to England, and had encouraged poor people, especially young women, to leave the squalor of their homeland and emigrate to Australia. Her work in Victoria was in providing clean, cheap and safe accommodation to families or single people on the way to the Mount Alexander diggings. She pressured the government into a scheme to built ten shelter sheds, which would provide accommodation for single men, single women and families. While none of the sheds lasted, the park is in the rough area where the sheds were located.

Yarra Ranges National Park. Named after Cumberland Creek (2). Established 1923 (Forests Commission tourist reserve) and 1929; the word Memorial was added to the name in 1994. A memorial, suggested by nursing sisters Bolam and McGowan [Mary Kenealy], to Australians who died during the First and Second World Wars and later conflicts. Includes the Cambarville picnic area, the Cumberland walking track, the Cumberland and Corra Linn Falls, lookouts, The Big Culvert, an historic water-race, fine stands of mountain ash and myrtle beech, the Big Tree (83 m high Eucalyptus regnans), and a Sitka spruce (Picea sitchensis) marking the site of the home of George Loch, timber cutter and gold miner, who lived there until 1938. Leadbeater's possum was rediscovered in the area in 1961.

Cyril Edward Fox (1921-2006) left school at the age of 14 years and worked at the Islington Railway Workshops until World War II broke out. He then joined the Australian Navy in April 1940.  In 1946 Cyril was drafted to the Flinders Naval Depot to do a physical training course after which he was sent to New
Guinea. When he returned he was appointed to the Naval College as a Physical Training Instructor.  He retired from the Navy in 1961 after completing 21 years of service.
Cyril commenced a new occupation with the Education Department of Victoria as Physical Education teacher at Aspendale Technical School. He also taught at Dromana and Frankston before retiring from teaching.
He was a Hastings Shire Councillor, representing Bittern, and a Shire President.
He was on the Crib Point Swimming Pool Advisory Committee in 1980-81, the Hastings Red Cross Committee, and the Crib Point Primary School Committee in 1981.  C.E. Fox was also a Justice of the Peace.
The Cyril Fox Bushland Reserve is a 2.3 hectare reserve of high quality remnant vegetation adjacent to the Cyril Fox Recreation Reserve.

The watercourse rises south-west of Yea, crosses the Goulburn Valley Highway and drains into the Goulburn River E.S.E. of Kerrisdale. The locality or small settlement is west of the creek at the junction of Homewood Road and Dairy Creek Road. A school, officially called Doogallook, but known locally as Dairy Creek, operated intermittently at the north end of Dairy Creek Road from 1882. It was moved further south in 1889, and officially renamed Dairy Creek. It closed in 1916, when the Homewood school opened after being moved to Dairy Creek Road. The creek may well have been named after the dairy near the Doogallook homestead in John Cotton's time.  See also Doogallook and Creamery Hill.

Parish; town; former pastoral run? The parish of Darlingford was originally on the south side of the Goulburn River on both sides of the Big River; it included a thin strip of land south of the Goulburn River between the confluences with the Goulburn of Jerusalem Creek and the Delatite River. The town (surveyed 1864) was on the Big River very near its junction with the Goulburn River, near the present Darlingford Reach and Darlingford Point (Point Knight). Named after Sir Charles (Henry) Darling (1809-70), governor of Victoria (1863-66). Darling is the Old English deorling, which had the same meaning a thousand years ago as now. The town was also known in its early days as The Junction or Big River Junction. Darlingford and Enoch's Point (q.v.) sprang up as a result of the discovery of gold on the Big River in 1854. There were schools at Darlingford from the 1860s, but there was also a Darlingford State School at Peachey's Bridge (q.v.). Darlingford township was submerged (ca. 1927), with much of the parish, by the filling of the Sugarloaf Reservoir, but see also New Darlingford. Spreadborough & Anderson's maps show a Darlingford pastoral run, but neither they nor Billis & Kenyon mention it in the text. The Borothat run, to the west of Darlingford on the map, looks too small. The Darlingford run may well be a mapping error for part of the Borothat run.

Named after Desmond 'Des' Ignatius Custerson, a well known Dandenong identity and, with his wife Maureen, started the Chubbies Dance Band. They remained the core members of the band for 50 years. The Chubbies Dance Band played at the old Workingman's Club in Dandenong and was the first band to play there when it was renovated. The band was the heart and soul of the well-known Lyndale Dance and raised funds for the Dandenong and District Hospital for 28 years. The band also played at dances all over Victoria to raise funds for charities such as the Make-A-Wish Foundation, Yooralla, the Helicopter Search & Rescue Service and local churches and communities. Des played the last gig with the Chubbies Dance Band at aged 84. Des also had a long association with the St Mary's Parish Football Club (he coached the Midgets for almost 15 years) and the Dandenong Football Club, through his son Neil. Des and Maureen lived in Sunset Grove, Dandenong for over 25 years with their five children. They were well known and respected in the local community. Des and Maureen embraced the diversity of Dandenong and always welcomed new migrants to the area. He was a gentle and ethical man that shared his love of Dandenong and football with his neighbours. Des passed away in April 2016.

Dexters Bush is named after Paul & Elizabeth Dexter in recognition of their efforts and the considerable time in nurturing and maintaining the bushland at the rear of their property in Dickasons Road Heathmont.
The Dexters purchased 5 acres of bushland, running from Dickasons Road to the Dandenong Creek in 1956. They gifted part of the land to Victoria Conservation Trust in 1988 and continued to be actively involved in preserving the bushland through their role on the committee of management, by assisting with plans, strategies and policies to promote the regeneration of the indigenous flora that was present in the soil and other significant species.   The Dexters stepped back from their role in the management of the bushland in 2015 and the land was transferred to Maroondah Council on 23 January 2018. The community and Council have always recognised the bushland as Dexters Bush.
Also to celebrate Queen Victoria's Diamond Jubilee.

Leading Aircraftsman William Allan, 49587, RAAF (1 Aircraft Depot). Son of William Decker. Enlisted at Melbourne 15 January 1942 and was discharged 26 March 1946. Died in Warragul 11 March 1976 and is buried in the Warragul Cemetery.

Corporal William (Bill), 431, 39 Infantry Battalion (B Company). Age 22 years 11 months, Labourer, single. Born at Warragul, Victoria. Son of Jacob Elliott
and Emily Decker (nee Jones) of Church Street, Warragul. Brother of Lance Corporal 4092 Albert Decker, 22 Infantry Battalion who was killed in action
at Broodseinde 9 October 1917: and Warrant Officer Class II 882 Jacob Elliott Decker, 8 Infantry Battalion. On the Warragul Fire Brigade, Warragul State School, and Warragul Shire Honour Boards. Bill enlisted at Warragul on 17 December 1915 and embarked at Melbourne per HMAT A11 Ascanius on 27 May 1916. Disembarked Devonport 18 July 1916. Proceeded to France 8 October 1916. Taken on strength of 8 Infantry Battalion 8 October 1916; and 46 Infantry
Battalion on 10 October 1916. Appointed to Lance Corporal 6 October 1917; and Corporal 20 January 1919. Returned to Australia on Orita 6 August 1919. Discharged 13 October 1919. Died 18 October 1974 and is buried in the Warragul Cemetery.

DECKER, Lance Corporal Albert, 4092, 22 Infantry Battalion (10 Reinforcement Group). Age 18 years 3 months, Labourer, single. Born at Warragul, Victoria. Son of Jacob Elliott and Emily Decker (nee Jones) of Church Street, Warragul. Educated at Warragul State School. Served with the Senior Cadets prior to his enlistment. Brother of Company Sergeant Major 882 Jacob Elliott Decker, 8 Battalion; and Corporal 431 William Decker, 39 Battalion. On the Warragul War Memorial, and the Warragul State School, and Warragul Shire Honour Boards. Albert enlisted Melbourne 23 December 1915 and embarked at Melbourne on HMAT A18 Wiltshire 7 March 1916. Disembarked at Suez 10 April 1916. Embarked Alexandria 9 May 1916 and disembarked Marseilles 18 May 1916. Taken on the strength of 22 Infantry Battalion from reinforcements 31 July 1916. Wounded in action 1 August 1916 when he sustained shrapnel wounds to his shoulder and a gunshot wound to his leg and was admitted to 3 Canadian Stationary Hospital at Boulogne. Transferred to England on the Hospital Ship Cambria 8 August 1916 and admitted to 2 Western General Hospital, Manchester. Rejoined his battalion 24 November 1916. Appointed Lance Corporal 15 May 1917. Albert was killed in action 9 October 1917 during the ferocious fighting near Passchendaele, Belgium. During September and early October the Allies steadily drove the Germans back to the top of Passchendaele ridge. Through October and into November, wet weather and sheer exhaustion meant further attacks became hopelessly bogged down. Though the final ridge was eventually gained, no breakthrough was possible. Losses were horrendous on both sides. Official War Historian Charles Bean wrote: I have often thought that many a youngster when he was hit out there on the Passchendaele heights ... and he knew that the end had come - must have thought to himself: "well at least they'll remember me in Australia." Albert is buried at White House Cemetery (III.H.26), St. Jean-les-Ypres, West-Vlaanderen,
Belgium.

(also Eglington, Eglintoun). Pastoral run (3,500 ha, 1845-81 or later), along the north side of Eglinton Creek (but see also Mount Pleasant run). Noble says that the run was named by Archibald Thom (licensee, 1845-48) after Eglintoun on the Tamar River, Tasmania (which the Thoms had left in 1834). The name is ultimately derived from Eglinton near Irvine in Scotland (from the Saxon name Ægelwine and Old English tun, enclosure). John Downey intended to use Eglinton for the town that became Alexandra (q.v.).

On Friday 7 December, 1951, a 49-year-old housewife named Mrs. Elsie Dorrington became the Shire of Mornington's first woman Councillor, when six hundred ratepayers decided to break with tradition of no women in the Shire Council. Cr. Dorringtons' first job was to urge the Council to set up a home-help scheme and she also went on to initiate a number of social welfare schemes in the Shire. Mrs Dorrington served three terms as Councillor until 1958. In 1960 Mrs Dorrington was appointed as Victorian Justice of the Peace and sat on the bench at Mornington's Magistrates Court. From 1961 to 1969, Mrs Dorrington worked for the Department of Mental Hygiene as the Manager of Moorakyne Girls Hostel in Hawthorn. Elsie Dorrington passed away on 1 June, 1995 in Mount Eliza.

With the support of the Congupna community the park name recognises the Farrell family.

The first generation of Farrell's in the district were William & Cecilia Farrell who moved to Congupna Road in 1889.

In 1924 their son William A (Bill) Farrell and his wife Ivy purchased land in Congupna. This was the second generation of the Farrell family in Congupna. William and Ivy had ten children. Originally called Burial Hill, this rise at the western end of the city grid was renamed when the flagstaff was erected in September 1840 for signalling shipping activities in Hobsons Bay. George Gordon McCrae reminisced that 'Bunting and great wicker balls' told what type of vessel was approaching and the port of origin. Marryat's code of signal flags was used to carry news from Williamstown. The advent of the telegraph rendered the flagstaff redundant and operation ceased on 1 October 1857. The signaller's store and dwelling were incorporated into the Flagstaff Observatory. At 130 ft (39.6 m) in height, and with better sight lines of Williams-town and the bay, Flagstaff Hill had been preferred to Batmans Hill as the observatory site. The Flagstaff Gardens were planted on the site in the 1860s.

Flagstaff Gardens is the oldest park in Melbourne, Victoria, Australia, first established in 1862. In 2005 it is one of the most visited and widely used parks in the city by nearby office workers and tourists. The gardens are notable for their archaeological, horticultural, historical and social significance to the history of Melbourne. The gardens are 7.2 hectares (18 acres) of Crown Land bounded by William, La Trobe, King and Dudley streets, managed by the City of Melbourne. On the south-east corner opposite is the entrance to Flagstaff railway station. Diagonally opposite stands the Victorian branch of the Royal Mint, established 7 August 1869. The former Royal Mint building is a well-preserved example of Victorian Gold Rush boom-period classical styled architecture. The facade features paired columns with scrolled capitals and the Royal Mint coat-of-arms. On the northeast corner over William Street, is the Queen Victoria Market. The park contains extensive lawns with a variety of mature trees, flowerbeds and wild animals including possums. The southern end is characterised by deciduous trees, while the northern end contains mature eucalypts. Avenues of elms shade pathways along with several large Moreton Bay Fig trees. The north corner contains a bowling lawn, rose beds, flower and shrub beds. Along William Street there are tennis courts, which also double as volleyball, handball and netball courts. Electric barbecues nearby provides a popular site for office parties in December. Scattered about the lawns and gardens are memorials and sculptures that illuminate some of the social significance of the area. http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flagstaff_Gardens

Foxeys Hangout on the corner of Balnarring and Tubbarubba Roads, Merricks North has been a local landmark since the 1930's. It is reminiscent of the days when trapping of wild animals was essential for the farmers' livelihoods. The name was originally given to a conspicuous gum tree near the corner by neighbouring landowners who initiated a friendly contest between two trappers as to who took more foxes. The catches were hung from the tree and a tally was kept.

In the late 1850s,a Djargurd wurrung clan head, 'King Alick', was given several acres of land near Camperdown. When he died in 1860, 'Prince Albert' his son, sought to have this land transferred to his possession. However, given the urban expansion of Camperdown, the grant was cancelled, and another reserve in the worse accessible locality near Camperdown was proposed. The Framlingham mission station was established near Warrnambool in 1865 and this station became the home of many of the surviving Djargurd wurrung. A number of old people, however, refused to abandon their traditional country. By 1877, there were only two aged Djargurd wurrung men living in the Camperdown district. They lived near a brewery and were well cared for by local town residents, but would not go to Framlingham.

Frank Jones (1917-1988). Long standing local resident, spent 36 years living at 1 Simpson Street. He enlisted in the AIF in Sale on 4 November 1939, and served with distinction in Egypt, the Middle East, Greece and Crete. He was discharged medically unfit for active service on 9 December 1943 as a result of being severely wounded during the Battle of Crete. After the war he worked with the Sale Council in the sanitary department, then was employed on the construction of sewering Sale. Because of his size and strength he constructed all the manholes for the project.On the completion of this project he worked with the Victorian Railways for the last 20 years of his working life operating from the Sale Railway yards. He looked after the reserve area

(north-west of Yea). Major meeting place for the Taungurong; parish; former pastoral run; goldfield settlement. James Henry Campbell, first licensee, bestowed the name on the pastoral run (1838-70 or later) of about 6,000 ha. (The homestead still exists.) Listed by Wells (1848, as Ghinghin). Gold was discovered in August 1867, and three reefs worked. In its heyday the township had 13 houses, two shops and "innumerable shanties and huts built by the several thousand hopeful miners and fossickers who flocked there" (Blanks). The goldfield was sometimes called Palestine Creek (Flett, 1970). Ghin Ghin is Aboriginal (Taungurong): "deep dark waters" (Les Blake); "supposed to mean Green Grass" (Blanks); "meeting of the waters" (Jones & Jones: 1); "meeting of waters" (Clark & Heydon: M); but, because of the doubling of ghin, may mean very - or lots of - something (big meeting place?). See also Palestine Creek.

Parish, township, pastoral run, goldfield. The Gobur pastoral run (about 2,400 ha, 1845-74 or later) was named by Henry Godfrey, licensee (1845-46), and was listed in 1848 by Wells (as "Gobier"). Aboriginal (presumably Taungurong): Les Blake gives goburr(a), kookaburra, and Clark & Heydon (M) gobur, kookaburra, but in closely related Woiworung, gurrborra means koala (Barry Blake). The township, once much larger than now, was also known as Godfrey's Creek, O'Brientown (Moyle & Davies) and Pennington(s) - after Ezekial Wilson Pennington (Flett, 1970). Waghorn (p. 6) gives a sketch map of Gobur in the gold-mining days which includes a number of features not named on survey maps. Some of these features can be located on modern maps with reasonable accuracy: see Burnt Hill, Cummins Hill, Mount Gobur and Stockade Gully; but three cannot be identified with certainty: Bald Hill (east to north east of Gobur), 82 Camp Hill (north of Bald Hill), and School Hill (south of Bald Hill).

Named after Lieutenant General Leslie James Morshead

Leslie Morshead won fame as the defender of Tobruk during the Second World War and is among the most renowned Australian divisional commanders of that war. He was born at Ballarat in Victoria on 18 September 1889 and became a teacher. Joining the AIF in September 1914 as a lieutenant, Morshead was posted to the 2nd Battalion. 

By the time he landed at Gallipoli on 25 April 1915 he was a captain; by August, when he fought at Lone Pine, he had been promoted to major. After Gallipoli he was promoted to lieutenant colonel and given command of the 33rd Battalion, which arrived in France in November 1916. Morshead led the battalion successfully through Messines and the Passchendaele campaign of late-1917, was awarded the Distinguished Service Order, and continued to command through the battles Villers-Bretonneux and Amiens in 1918. 

Morshead joined General Monash's staff for the demobilisation of the AIF and returned to Sydney in December 1919. He married Myrtle Woodside in November 1921. Having failed to make a success of a soldier-settlers' block in Queensland, Morshead returned to Sydney to work in shipping, gaining promotions and posts in several Australian cities and in England. 

He remained active in the militia, commanding two battalions and reaching the rank of temporary brigadier. In October 1939 he was given command of the 18th Brigade, sailing for Britain in May 1940. The following February Morshead was promoted to major general in command of the 9th Division, then in the Middle East. Reputed to be a tough commander who could be blunt with senior officers, Morshead led his division through the siege of Tobruk where his aggressive defence denied the Germans a breakthrough but earned him the ire of some subordinates concerned at the level of losses. 

His success at Tobruk was followed by promotion to lieutenant general and command of the AIF in the Middle East. Morshead, at the risk of alienating his British superiors, argued to keep the 9th Division together in the face of British demands to detach individual brigades. He led the division through the battle of El Alamein, where the 9th Division's contribution was considered vital to the victory. During the battle, he regularly visited both the front and the wounded behind the lines. 

Returning to Australia in 1943, Morshead took command of II Corps in October and then in November was elevated to command both New Guinea Force and the Second Australian Army. In May 1944 he was given command of I Corps, leading them through the final battles of the war in Borneo. After the war, he chaired a military court of enquiry into Major General Bennett's departure from Singapore in February 1942. 

Morshead refused offers of military and diplomatic posts, as well as the governorship of Queensland, returning instead to the shipping industry as manager of the New South Wales branch of the Orient Line; later he became its Australian general manager. He held a number of other directorships and civil appointments and was involved in right-wing politics before becoming ill with cancer in the mid-1950s. Morshead died in Sydney on 26 September 1959.

Harold Caterson was a member of Moorabbin Rugby Union Football Club's first committee, he was at the initial meeting in December 1964 that agreed to create a rugby club in Moorabbin to commence in season 1965. He was a long-term committee member (in various positions) and club member in the 60s, 70s and 80s and he was key in establishing a home for Moorabbin at Keys. Rd. Additionally, he was involved on the Management Committee of the Victorian Rugby Union over many years.
In the history of the club Harold Caterson and Jack McDavitt stand out as the two most influential club members who founded, developed and built Moorabbin Rugby Club from scratch.
Jack has, appropriately, had the extended clubrooms (originally built in 1978) named in his honour for his contribution to the club. The reserve was renamed in honour of Harold's contribution to the club.

Keys Rd ground was an old rubbish tip that had been filled and covered in a layer of soil. The surface was continually subsiding, in 1965 junior cricket was played on this ground and the oval was found unsuitable for cricket; it was actually a muddy paddock in winter and a corrugated concrete oval in summer. Cricket never returned to this oval.
Harold could see the potential in the Keys Rd Reserve and in 1967 donated the cost of a single car steel garage placed on a concrete slab, which was to become our first changing room/clubroom, and was later known as "the old tin shed". It had the nickname of "Mr. Cat's Cottage" on a sign above the door.
The following year a small extension was added that held a briquette hot water service and several showers.
As the Club grew over the years, Harold continued to be a committee member and also continued to liaise with Council regarding club matters. Whether it was gaining approval for further extensions to the shed (there were several extensions over the years), ground improvements, a second playing field, flood lighting and eventually Clubrooms were built in 1978.
Harold was the "go to person" in regard to Council. He developed a very good relationship with Mayor Bricker, who later became our Patron for many years and over time became one of the Rams strongest supporters.
Gaining significant funding for a sport that was practically unknown in the district, was not easy. The relationship between Harold and Cr. Bricker proved vital on several occasions as the councillor supported funding for the club which otherwise might not have been approved.
That the Rams are based at Keys Road can be put down to Harold's dedication to securing a permanent home for rugby union in Moorabbin.

The club's playing jersey is also a legacy from Harold Caterson's U18 Marlins team.
He was President in 1968 and 1971; Vice President in 1969, 1970 and from 1972 to 1981 inclusive. Ordinary Committee Member 1965 to 1967.
Harold was made a Life Member in 1977.
Additionally, he was the Moorabbin club delegate to the Victorian Rugby Union for many years; and he would collate the results and statistics for the VRU weekly magazine each week during the season.
His work with the club, Council and the VRU continued right up to his sudden death in 1981.
It is worth noting that four generations of the Caterson family have been involved in playing and administrating the Moorabbin Rugby Club since its inception in 1965.

Albert Jacka was born on 10 January 1893 at Layard near Winchelsea, Victoria, fourth child of Nathaniel Jacka and his wife Elizabeth, nÃ¿Â¿Ã¿Â©e Kettle. The family moved to Wedderburn when Albert was 5. After elementary schooling, Bert worked for the Victorian State Forests Department. 
Jacka enlisted in September 1914 as a private in the 14th Battalion, Australian Imperial Force. His unit spent two months training in Egypt before landing at Anzac Cove on 26 April 1915. On 19 May the Turks launched a massive counter-attack. Amid frenzied fighting at Courtney's Post some Turks captured a 11m section of trench, one end of which was guarded by Jacka. For several minutes he fired warning shots into the trench wall until reinforcements arrived and, after shouting his instructions, he and three others sprang out into the trench. All but Jacka were immediately hit so he leapt back into the communication trench. Two bombs were lobbed at the Turks while Jacka skirted around to attack from the flank. Amid the smoke and the noise he clambered over the parapet, shot five Turks and bayoneted two as the rest hastily retreated. For this action he received the Victoria Cross, the first to be awarded to the A.I.F. in the war.
Jacka became a national hero. He rose quickly through the ranks, passing officer training and was commissioned 2nd lieutenant in April 1916.
Jacka's platoon moved into the line near PoziÃ¿Â¿Ã¿Â¨res, France, on the night of 6-7 August 1916. German troops overran a part of the line at dawn. Jacka had just completed a reconnaissance and had gone to his dug-out when two Germans appeared at its entrance and rolled a bomb down the doorway, killing two men. Jacka charged up the dug-out steps, firing as he moved, and came upon a large number of the enemy rounding up some forty Australians as prisoners. He rallied his platoon and charged at the enemy, some of whom immediately threw down their rifles. Furious hand-to-hand fighting erupted as the prisoners turned on their captors. Fifty Germans were captured and the line was retaken. Jacka was awarded a Military Cross. The entire platoon was wounded, Jacka seriously in the neck and shoulder. He received further promotions. 
On 8 April 1917 Jacka led a night reconnaissance party into no man's land near Bullecourt to inspect enemy defences before an attack against the new German line. He penetrated the wire at two places, reported back, then went out again to supervise the laying of tapes to guide the infantry. The work was virtually finished when two Germans loomed up. Realizing that they would see the tapes, Jacka knew that they must be captured. He pulled his pistol; it misfired, so he rushed on and captured them by hand.For  this action he was awarded a Bar to his Military Cross.
He was wounded by a sniper's bullet near Ploegsteert Wood on 8 July. In May 1918 he was badly gassed at Villers-Bretonneux and saw no more action. In September 1919 he embarked for Australia where a large crowd, met him. He was demobilized in January 1920. Shortly after his return he formed an import export business with two former comrades. 
On 17 January 1921 Jacka had married Frances Veronica Carey, a typist from his office. They settled at St Kilda and later adopted a daughter. In September 1929 Jacka was elected to the St Kilda Council and became mayor a year later. He devoted most of his energies on council to assisting the unemployed. His own business flourished until 1929 when the Scullin government increased import tariffs and the company went into voluntary liquidation in September 1930. Jacka then became a commercial traveller with the Anglo-Dominion Soap Co.
He died on 17 January 1932. Nearly 6000 people filed past his coffin when it lay in state in Anzac House. The funeral procession, led by over 1000 returned soldiers flanked by thousands of onlookers, made its way to St Kilda cemetery where he was buried with full military honours.

The name Jordanville dates from 1930 when it was given to the railway station, newly opened on the line from East Malvern to Glen Waverley. Other names had been considered, including St Johns Wood, the name of an estate to the north of the station that had recently been acquired by the Riversdale golf club. The choice of Jordanville came about from the Jordan family, particularly John Jordan who was an early settler and shire councillor.

Joseph Harris arrived from England in 1856 and initially made his name as a nurseryman. He was chairman of the metropolitan parks and gardens board and was connected with the Burnley Horticultural Society and with the landscaping of the a number of years and was knighted for his services. In the late 1800's he acquired the site of the Scout Camp, with an early emphasis on the planting of exotic species. On his death in 1925 the family gave the land to the Boy Scouts Association and in 1932 the Governor and Chief Scout of Victoria, Lord  Somers, officially opened the Scout Camp.

WURRUMBIT BIRRNG YAAR
Meaning: Long waterhole in the Merri River at Woodford.
Source: Dawson 1881
Pronunciation: WOO-ROOM-BIT BEER-NG YAR

It is clear from historical records the original local Aboriginal name for the site now known as Jubilee Park was as indicated above. It is normally the case with places of importance to Aboriginal people that several names are evident and are in close proximity to each other.  This demonstrates the local clan/s particular relationship with each site.

Raymond "John" Hall was born 12 June 1948. Always known as John, his love of cricket started as a junior and as an adult he became a first and second division
premiership captain with the Mildura West Cricket Club. He coached junior cricket over many years and the club was like his second home. He was also a life member of the Sunraysia Cricket Association.

John was president of the Mildura West Cricket Club for over 25 years and was instrumental in the club moving to the Old Aerodrome sporting complex. John
orchestrated significant fund raising to assist in the construction of the facilities that exist today. No job was too large and he was never too busy to give tasks or people the time they deserved.

The Mildura West Cricket Club nickname "The Toads" is named after John, in recognition of a man that gave a lot more that he took. John sadly passed away 4
September 2010, aged 62.

Parish, settlements. From 1862 two small settlements sprang up, one serving the Luck's All and Star of the West mines called Mack's Creek; the other was 1.5 km to the north on the Mansfield Woods Point Road around J. S. Garrett's beer house (today's Kevington Hotel). The Mack's Creek settlement was surveyed and renamed Kevington, after the village in Kent, but failed to prosper, and the name Kevington was readopted by the township on the main road. The last two syllables of Kevington are probably from Old English -inga(s), people, and tun, enclosure, homestead, village, (though the ing in -ington is sometimes just a suffix), in which case the first syllable will be an Anglo-Saxon personal name such as Cyfa or Cafa.

At one time, long years ago, there was a very large redgum tree growing in the lake, and its branches supported a tremendously large nest, the property of an immensely large pair of wedge-tailed eagles (Nurrayil'). One fine day a young mother wandered carrying her baby, a long way round the lake, and far from the camp, when, feeling tired, she sat down and amusedly watched her baby playing in the warm sand, when suddenly, and without warning, the larger of the two eagles swooped down and, seizing the baby, carrying it away over the water to its eyrie in the red gum tree. The poor mother, seeing her baby suddenly lost to her for ever, commenced a mournful wailing, which the curlews or stone plovers ('Will') in sympathy took up, and have continued ever since. The disconsolate young mother then hurried back to the camp and reported the occurrence, upon which the doctor or medicine-man ('Barngnull') directed that every person with a canoe was to proceed to the tree, and after cutting it down to tear it into little pieces, and to boat it all away to the river, where it was to be thrown upon the water to be carried away. The doctor then decreed that no more trees should grow in Lake Boga. The tree is falling hollowed out with its branches a big depression near the river, which they called 'Geranyuk' (where the branches and leaves fell). The large gnarled lump on the tree trunk struck and hollowed out a big hole at the entrance to the lake, which they named 'Wherpook' (where butt fell). (Stone 1911: 461).

Said by Kenyon in his Story of the Mallee 'to have been named by Morgan, the bushranger, after a favourite steed. He was in the habit of traversing the Mallee by the Pine Plains - Kulkyne Track when one place or the other got too hot for him. He was eventually shot in 1865m at Peechelba.' Massola says it is more likely the horse is named after the lake, and that the name comes from local Aboriginal mythology in which two brothers Bram-bram-bult are involved. The dam in the bed of the lake was excavated in 1962. The lake filled in 1976 causing seedling regeneration of River Red-gum along the high water mark.

Massola says it is more likely the horse is named after the lake, and that the name comes from local Aboriginal mythology in which two brothers Bram-bram-bult are involved. The dam in the bed of the lake was excavated in 1962. The lake filled in 1976 causing seedling regeneration of River Red-gum along the high water mark.

The Lord Somers Camp at Somers was set up by the then Governor of Victoria, Lord Somers, in 1931. Lord Somers aimed to duplicate the success of the popular United Kingdom Duke of York Camps where up to 400 teenage boys from public schools and industry could meet and mix for a week. The Camp has been highly praised for its country club character, with its own sewerage system, hot water and electricity, reticulated fresh water and a open air cinema. Lord Somers had a remarkable career with a highly developed sense of duty and leadership. Career highlights included his distinguished World War 1 service, Governor of Victoria  from 1926 to 1931, grand master of the United Grand Lodge of Victoria and his long term involvement with the scout movement as the Victorian chief commissioner in 1932 and as chief scout for Great Britain in 1941.

Parish, settlement, former railway station (1891 - 1978) and pastoral run. The village was named after a pastoral run (1846-66) of about 11,000 ha (originally part of Watson and Hunter's Run). The run was east of the present township. According to Robinson (journal, 12 May 1840), Brough Smyth (1878) and Clark & Heydon (M) originally the Taungurong name for The Paps (q.v.). Massola (1968) and Saxton say the word means woman's breasts, but Barry Blake records breast in Taungurong as birring or birrm-birrm.) Clark & Heydon (D) give variants Men-dum-bul (from Robinson), Meendumbile and Meendumble. See also Redfern Point and Royal Town.

Parish, between Brankeet and Eildon parishes to the north and south, and between Yarck and Wappan parishes to the west and east. School (1886-95, 1901-03). Pastoral run (occasionally called Devils' River Station), established 1838, of 11,650 ha along the Delatite River north of Eildon; subdivided, 1861, into Maintongoon East and West (q.v.). Aboriginal (presumably Taungurong). According to Les Blake from matong, great, strong, and ngune, you; but these words have probably been taken from Reed (1969), and ngune is given by Reed as South Australian. Gillison says the name means large lagoon, and was at first spelt Maitongoon. This spelling occurs in a map of ca. 1866, though an earlier map (1856) gives Maitongorn. The last syllable just might be from gurnung, river or creek in Taungurong and Woiworung.

Town, parish, shire, former railway station. A settlement, at first called The Battery (after nearby Mount Battery), grew up around a forge built by Alfred Chenery for a blacksmith named Deedy. The town was renamed in 1856 either after Edward Eyre Mansfield (resident in 1841) or, more likely, at the suggestion of Charles Dickens (manager of the Preston pastoral run), after Mansfield, Nottinghamshire (from Maun, Celtic river name, and Old English feld, clearing). Beolite was proposed but not adopted. Rail services arrived in October 1891, and finally ceased in November 1978. The railway station is now a visitors' information centre. The shire of Mansfield, first created in 1866, was incorporated into the shire of Delatite in 1994 but re-established in 2002.

Parish; locality (1160 m alt.), junction of the Warburton Woods Point Road and Walhalla Road. Gold discovered, 1861. The township began (1863) as Emerald Hill, but was renamed (1864 or '65) after Matlock, Derbyshire - Old English mæþ(e)l, meeting, council, moot, and ac, oak - to avoid confusion with the Melbourne suburb of Emerald Hill* (later South Melbourne*). A number of "suburbs" or satellite settlements sprang up, including Alhambra (q.v.), Harper's Creek, Mutton Town* and Toorak (after the Melbourne suburb; Woiworung or Bunurong Turrak*: reedy swamp, reedy grass, or weed in lagoon). Toorak was soon renamed Thackeray (after writer William Makepeace Thackeray). A bushfire in 1873 wiped out almost all the buildings and, as the road to Woods Point had been rerouted away from the hill, Matlock was rebuilt at the new crossroads on the site of the former Thackeray. The old site became or was renamed Matlock Hill (q.v.). Just south of Matlock are the headwaters of B.B. Creek* which (further down) had its own goldfield and settlement. (B.B. probably stands for Bare Buttocks, as the creek's vegetation was reputedly very rough on miners' clothing.) See also The Springs.

Parish. Former pastoral run (6,500 ha, 1851-77) on the west bank of the Acheron River west and north-west of Buxton. Also called Jones's Station after Stephen Jones (licensee, 1856-60?). All or part of this land became the second and possibly third sites of the Acheron Aboriginal Station (q.v.), and thereafter was sometimes also called the Blacks' Station. Kenyon's map shows the Mohican run too far north, and makes the adjoining Taggerty run too small. Spreadborough & Anderson's maps show the Mohican run correctly (perhaps extending a bit too far south). Mohican persists as a parish name and in the Mohican Plantation. Les Blake thinks the name was probably taken from James Fennimore Cooper's novel, The Last of the Mohicans (1826); if so, the word is a variant of the North American tribal name Mohegan (Algonquian maingan, wolf), a subgroup of the Pequot, and probably their relatives the Mahican (Muh-he-con-ne-ok, people of waters that are never still) (Waldman). The Victorian name might be a squatterese version of an Aboriginal word or name.

The pastoral property was originally called Morangourke, believed to be derived from the Aboriginal word 'Murrangurk', the name of a native that was bestowed on the English convict William Buckley, who escaped captivity and lived with the Wathaurong people for many years. Legend has it that Buckley was found by the Wathaurong people carrying a piece of broken spear that had been placed on the grave of Murrangurk. Thus Buckley was identified with Murrangurk and, 'as one returned from the grave', received his name. Moranghurk is understood to have several meanings, two of which are 'stone axe handle' and 'reincarnated warrior'.
Moranghurk may refer to Murrangurrk, an Aboriginal person.

Brankeet Inlet, Lake Eildon. Named after Scottish-born Ann Fraser Bon née Dougall (1838 - 1936, nom-de-plume "Sylvia", nicknamed "The Widow of Wappan"). She compensated for her innate shyness by becoming a formidable champion of the Taungurong and other Aboriginals, demanded an investigation (1881) into conditions at Coranderrk (q.v.) and served on the board of inquiry. She was founder of a school for Chinese children (in Melbourne*), a benefactor of the Austin Hospital (Melbourne*), and an advocate of humane treatment for the mentally ill. (A.D.B. 7.) See also Wappan. Bon is an Old French name derived from Latin bonus, good.

Alexander (Alec) and Patricia (Pat) McGregor were unable to have children of their own, but were extremely dedicated to the community. Their input went above and beyond the normal assistance offered by other community members and volunteers. Both Alec and Pat are the only life members of the Junior Football Club (of which the reserve is home to), and they have been heavily involved in all community groups over their respective lives. Pat had also been the local kindergarten assistant for over 30 years, and they were both well known and adored in the community. The couple bequeathed a large amount of money to all of these groups. The name change is in their honour as thanks for all of their generosity.
