Parish. A former forestry district with headquarters at Taggerty (q.v.). Former pastoral run (originally 6,500 ha) east of the Whanregarwen run and west of the Acheron run and the Acheron River; established 1839; subdivided, 1864, into Niagaroon (cancelled 1881) and Riversdale No. 1 (q.v.). The Niagaroon run probably extended further south than is shown in Spreadborough & Anderson's maps. Les Blake has suggested that Niagaroon may allude to Niagara Creek (see under Snobs Creek) to the east, but it is in fact an Anglicised form of the Taungurong Nyaggeron (or Ageroon), probably adopted by the first licensees Ouseley Cockburn and Dr. Dougald Fletcher, who also (according to Les Blake) named the Acheron River (q.v.).

Parish, locality north-west of Mansfield. "Indian name, blue house" (Saxton). Hindi: nila, blue, and kuti, cottage, hut, hermitage. This derivation would seem unlikely but for a remark by Massola (1968: 2): "Some surveyors and colonists introduced odd names from foreign languages, which sounded Aboriginal. One notorious example is that of J. C. W. Wilmot, the surveyor who among other places named Baddaginnie and Dookie. The first is a Ceylonese [Sinhalese] word. . . . The second is . . . Malay." Baddaginnie* and Dookie* are to the north of Nillahcootie. See also Lake Nillahcootie.

Pentridge Prison was established in 1851 as a result of increased pressure on the Penal system due to the gold rush and the need for a place to hold those convicted of serious offences. The first stage was the 1850-1857 Pentridge Stockade Complex, a relatively ad-hoc group of structures built by prison labour and using predominantly local materials. The second phase undertaken in the late 1850s and early 1860s was the construction of Inspector General William Champ's model prison complex, based on British exemplars and incorporating a relatively sophisticated system of prisoner classification and penal reform. The main structures constructed at this stage and still surviving are the Entrance Building, Warder's residences, Prison Hospital, Panopticon B Division, F Division, a Workshop building (now known as the Laundry) and most of the prison walls. These were all constructed of bluestone. The prison was gradually expanded and developed in stages, reflecting both developments in penology as well as broader Government policies relating to the operation of the prison system. Following the Stawell Royal Commission of 1870 an extensive work program for prisoners was introduced as part of the system at Pentridge and a complex known as the Industries was constructed. These included a timber yard, a woollen mill, carpenters' and blacksmiths' workshops completed in 1879 and tailors' and bootmakers' workshops completed in 1886. A female prison was constructed on the site between 1860 and 1865 which is now known as A Division. This was superseded when a new female prison was constructed on the site between 1887 and 1894 in order to provide completely separate accommodation for women. This section is now known as D Division. Pentridge remained the main female prison until it was replaced by the new women's prison, HM Prison Fairlea in 1956. Pentridge was also the location of reformatories for both girls and boys, established following the findings of the Stawell Royal Commission of 1870. The Jika Reformatory for Boys was accommodated in an existing building (F Division), between 1875 and 1879, while a purpose built reformatory was constructed for the Jika Reformatory for Protestant Girls (G Division), which operated between 1875 and 1893. In 1900 labour yards for A Division were completed. During the 1950s these yards were later converted to a high security block which became known as H Division. In 1924 Pentridge replaced the Melbourne Gaol as the main remand and reception prison for the metropolitan area. The bodies of a number of prisoners executed at the Melbourne Gaol were exhumed and relocated to Pentridge, where they were reburied, possibly just east of D Division. Pentridge also became the venue for all subsequent hangings, until the last Victorian prisoner to suffer the death penalty, Ronald Ryan was executed in D Division in 1967. In April 1995 the Office of Corrections ordered that the six main towers at Pentridge be closed, since most of the high security prisoners from the gaol had been relocated to Barwon as part of the downgrading of Pentridge to a medium security prison. The prison was finally closed in 1996.

Port Phillip Bay was originally named Port King in honour of Governor King. Governor King later changed it to Port Phillip in honour of the first Governor of New South Wales. Prior to 1851 and the establishment of the colony of Victoria, the general area south of the Murray River was called the Port Phillip District of New South Wales. To clearly distinguish between the District and the Bay in general usage, one was called Port Phillip District and the other Port Phillip Bay. The name Port Phillip Bay has remained in general usage ever since. In 1970, the Hydrographer of the Royal Australian Navy suggested that the word Bay be deleted from the name Port Phillip Bay. The Place Names Committee contacted all the municipalities around the Bay and other interested bodies for their views. In October 1972, after giving due consideration to all factors involved, the Place Names Committee decided that the name Port Phillip Bay should remain.  In 1994, a similar process resulted in the restoration of Port Phillip as the registered name.

Ralph Goode enlisted on 16 August 1914, the first man from Lilydale to do so. He was allotted to the 2nd Field Ambulance to serve as a stretcher bearer and he travelled on the SS Wiltshire in the first convoy to Egypt. He was stationed there until he moved to Lemnos Island and then was at the landing at Gallipoli. He saw service at Anzac Cove and Cape Helles and was there at the Battle of Lone Pine. He was Mentioned in Despatches for his work here. After the evacuation, he was sent back to Egypt where his unit was re-organised and then moved to France.
Between 1916 and 1918 he served on the Western Front, experiencing all the horrors and heroism of those campaigns. He was a veteran of Pozieres, Bullecourt, Passchendaele, Ypres and Delville Wood. In 1918 he returned home to Lilydale, married, had a family and took up a business running a drapers store in Lilydale's Main Street. He also did community work and achieved an extraordinary amount for that township. His family believed his way of coping with what he saw during the war years was to keep himself busy with community work. He was awarded the MBE for his efforts for that community. He died in 1961.

In the 17th century, the first Earl of Ranelagh built Ranelagh House just outside of London and in
1741 the Ranelagh Gardens were opened to the public. Ranelagh became a fashionable holiday resort and was the model for the development of the Mount Eliza Ranelagh in 1924. A number of Mount Eliza Ranelagh streets were named after London places. More specifically, the Mount Eliza Ranelagh was promoted as an area where people could build their holiday homes with recreational facilities, parks and internal reserves and a community focus. This approach was given full expression by Walter Burley Griffin and Marion Griffin who, consistent with their environmental and philosophical ideals, produced the 1924 plan.

This reserve is named in honour of two of Dromana's pioneering families: the Shaw family and the McKeown family.

The Shaw family (Benjamin and Elizabeth) arrived in Dromana in 1875 and established Kangerong Guest House. Their son Archibald Shaw married Maud McKeown, daughter of James and Catherine McKeown, and started the family connection. Archibald was elected President of the Flinders Shire Council in 1924. Archibald and Maud raised and educated five children in Dromana (Maurice, Ernest, Archibald, Elizabeth and John). Maurice was the long-term proprietor of the Shell Service Station in Dromana and Shaw's Motors on Nepean Highway for many years prior to his death in 1991 aged 87.

The McKeown family (James and Catherine) arrived in Dromana in 1864. James cut timber for the Dromana pier in 1874 and in 1889 bought Gracefield and land to the East, where they planted an apple orchard. That land covered the area on which the reserve is now located. From 1889 to 1891 they were caretakers at Heronswood and in 1892 the McKeowns built Aringa Guest House (Cnr of Clarendon and Foote Streets Dromana) which was managed by their daughters for over 70 years until after the Second World War. James and Catherine raised 12 children (five sons and seven daughters); one daughter, Edith, the source for the naming of Edith Place, died in Dromana in 1987 aged 100. Two further generations of the Shaw and McKeown families have since lived in Dromana.

The surrounding land and the land on which the reserve is located was subdivided by the descendants of the pioneering Shaws and McKeowns in 1977 and the reserve was transferred to the Shire of Flinders (and since Mornington Peninsula Shire) for use as public open space.

It commemorates the service and sacrifice of all Victorians who have served and died in wars since World War I (1914-18). It embodies the devastating impact of that war on the Australian nation, and Victoria in particular, which lost the largest proportion of its young men in the country. When the project was conceived, Melbourne was the capital of Australia and the seat of Federal Parliament and this resulted in the grandest war memorial in Australia, until the Australian War Memorial was built in Canberra in 1941. Since World War II (1939-45) numerous elements, including a commemorative forecourt, trees, statues and memorials, have been added to the Shrine Reserve to honour servicemen and women and peacekeepers from 1939 to the present day. As the largest and most important war memorial in Victoria, it reflects the community's ongoing need for a public expression of grief and of commemoration for the sacrifice of life in war.

Nicknamed after Mr Baker who owned the land for many years prior to the Second World War and after. During the early part of the war, the land was used as an Army training Camp where soldiers assembled from all over Victoria. In 1943, American soldiers from the Pacific region used the land as a recreation camp. Towards the end of the Second World War the site was used as a P.O.W camp including Italian prisoners. The nickname 'Starlight' originated because of Mr Baker's tendency to roam the land at night. He may have used his property for hunting because in those days it was virgin bushland and very isolated.

Previously called Checkingurk (or Tichingorouk) and settled by Captain James Reid in 1840, 'The Briars' had a long association with the Balcombe family.  The name was given to a number of Balcombe properties in Australia, all borrowing from a homestead in the hills above the Jamestown, capital of St Helena, an island in the Atlantic Ocean operated under charter by the East India Company.  The homestead garden included briar roses.  [See 'Balcombe Family and "The Briars" Park, Mt Martha, Victoria', and research papers held at 'The Briars'.
(710 m alt.), Cathedral Range State Park: clearing and camping site on the ridge near Jawbone Saddle. The local lyrebirds have learnt to mimic the sounds of various farm animals.

It was named after Aitken's Gap, which described a route between several hills in the district. The village was at the northern foot of a hill named Mount Tophet; another hill, Mount Aitken, is about 5 km north-west. The village was named after John Aitken, a Port Phillip pastoralist who took up the Mount Aitken run in 1836 and built his homestead a few kilometres west of The Gap.
Previously known as Aitken's Gap.  See also Aitken Hill.

Historical Information: Named after former resident, Val Boyd, who made a significant contribution as a community worker over many years in the Ferntree Gully area.

Born in Germany of Ukrainian parents, Valentina arrived first at Bonegilla in 1951, then moved to South Australia.  She returned to teach at Wodonga South Primary School and was a councillor for Bonegilla ward from 1985 to 1993.  She was Mayor of Wodonga in 1989 and was inaugural chairwoman of the Albury-Wodonga Regional Arts Board.

Named after the Van Cleef family, who were long standing residents of the Venus Bay district. Historical Information: The park was created as part of the residential development on the former Haig Street Primary School site. The park is named in honour of Vin Heffernan OAM, Councilor - City Of Heidelberg (1966-1985) Mayor (1979-80), State Member for Ivanhoe (1985-1996) and Minister for Small Business and Youth Affairs (1992-1996). There is a strong local connection to Vin Heffernan in Heidelberg Heights with the former Haig Street Primary School library, which stood on the site, named in his honour.

The park was formerly known as Vin Heffernan Reserve. It was renamed in 2016 in order to free up the name 'Vin Heffernan' for use in a more suitable location.
Community consultation to rename the reserve occurred in early 2016. The name Radio Park is in recognition of a radio relay tower which was formerly located near the site prior to its development.

The original Wagon Flat was a few kilometres to the south-west of the area on the Murrayville Track now known as Wagon Flat. It was flatter than much of the surrounding land with a good catchment and a good tank dug by the early settlers. In 1910 settler Hann woke in the night and found it had rained and his wagon and horses were in knee-deep water.

Walter Cottrell lived his whole life in Wodonga.  His main transport was his bicycle. He became a drover of sheep and cattle, then worked for Albert Schlink who owned the first store south of the railway line.  He cut wood for the quarry boilers during the construction of Hume Weir.  His last job was with the Army at Bandiana.  He was a champion shooter and a life member of the Wodonga Show Society.  He kept pigeons and was in demand all over Victoria as a show judge.

Parish. Pastoral run (12,000 ha, est. 1847, originally part of Watson and Hunter's Run) on the Delatite River, partly submerged by the Sugarloaf Weir, and further inundated by the Eildon Dam. Burial place of Baalwick, head of the Yeerun-illam-balluk band of the Taungurong; for many years the home of Scottish-born John Bon (1805-68) and his wife Ann, who gave the Taungurong people sanctuary here until they were resettled at Coranderrk (q.v.). Wappang was a Taungurong name probably for the Delatite River ("that part of the Devil's [sic] River on which the run was formed" - Noble). Clark & Heydon (D) suggest that Yallermeerrangan (Yallermeourung), mentioned in George Augustus Robinson's journal (1840) was the Taungurong name for the Wappan area. See also Mrs. Bon Bay, Point Tehan, Taungurong Creek and Wappan Block.

Wattle Park is the only Australian example of a comprehensively developed pleasure park established, owned and operated by a transport authority with the dual aim of promoting its transport services and providing a recreational facility for the public. The layout of the park and its buildings and structures remain intact in their original 1920s form. The name and theme of the park reflect the strong national fervour of the early decades of the century - the wattle is Australia's national floral emblem. It has a historical association with two prominent Melbourne identities, Orland Fenwick, a former lord mayor and Eliza Welch, widow of the co-founder of the retailing firm Ball & Welch, before it was purchased by the Hawthorn Tramways Trust.

Named after a local park. Previously owned by businessman and Mayor of Melbourne Orlando Fenwick and then by Eliza Welch, the 137-acre block was secured by the Hawthorn Tramway Trust in 1917 as a destination for its Riversdale Rd line. The adjacent suburb, developed for housing from the 1920s, came to share the name Wattle Park.
The name commemorates the Wattles Guest House that operated on the site from 1914 to 1960 (when the building was destroyed by fire).

Named after the Wieland family.  Carl Ferdinand Wieland (1827-1902) was an immigrant from Prussia who arrived in 1872.  He established the first orchard in the district with his wife Caroline.  He named the settlement of Heathmont after the heath growing on the low hilly slopes.  His grandsons, Norman and Stanley helped construct Heathmont's first railway station which opened in 1926. Stanley and his wife Thelma had an orchard in the area 1930 to 1950.  The reserve was formerly their horse paddock and dam.

Parish covering Mount Marianne and the lower portion of King Parrot Creek. Proposed name for a railway station at Kerrisdale (q.v.). Named after Lt.-Gen. Sir Charles (Ash) Windham (1810-70), who served in Canada, the Crimea and India, and was M.P. for East Norfolk (no connexion with Wyndham*, Vic., as Les Blake has suggested). The surname is ultimately from place-names such as Wyndham, Sussex - Old English personal name Winda and hamm, water meadow - or Wymondham, Leicestershire and Norfolk, from the Old English personal name Wigmund (wig, war, mund, protection, hand) and ham, homestead, estate, village. See also Yea.

Wilhelm Koschel arrived in Wodonga in 1878 from Prussia and settled with his widowed mother and siblings. They bought a farm on the Beechworth Wodonga Rd in 1880, was a successful winegrower before turning to dairying in the 1920s. The property was sold in 1951. Wilhelm and wife Amanda Olson reared 11 children; many descendants remain in the area.

Pronounced Woong-gur-will Durr-ung
The names means strong heart, and represents the following values:
- A centre such as this can become the heart of the community - both the local Wyndham Vale community, and the Wyndham-wide Aboriginal community.
- Strength of identity, strength of culture, strength of families, and strength of community will be outcomes of this centre, and the "strong heart" name reflects this.
- Uncle Bryon Powell, Wadawurrung elder, shared a story on the 'soak' located on the site, the importance of that to cultural practices and being a place where clans would have gathered for food. 
- It can serve as a reminder that the Wyndham Aboriginal community's heart continued to beat strongly, even when that community was disrupted, dispersed and without a specific home to meet in.

Parish, town, former shire (1873 - 1994), former railway station (1883 - 1978). Gold was discovered in the area in late 1851. State school Yea No. 699 was in Yea, but Yea No. 1433 (eventually renamed Homewood) was at Gill's Gully and Mount Charlotte. Yea was originally called Muddy Creek after the nearby river; surveyed 1855-56 by Thomas Wilkinson Pinniger (commemorative cairn and plaque in High Street; see also Mount Pinniger); renamed (1855) after Colonel Lacy Walter Giles Yea (1808-55) commander of the 7th Royal Fusiliers, who served with General Windham in the Crimean War and was fatally wounded at Redan near Sebastopol. (The surname rhymed with saw, the place-name now rhymes with say.) Harvey Blanks reckons the name change was proposed by surveyor-general Sir Andrew Clarke (1824 - 1902) and implemented after surveyor Pinniger had discussed it with William Leyden Ker and Anna Maria Ker of the Killingworth pastoral run. (See also "Antiquarian", Alexandra Times, 23 June 1868.) The new name was ironically appropriate as Yea - a variant of the Devon and Somerset surname Yeo - comes from the Old English ea, stream, river. See also Marshmallow Hill, Providence Bridge, Sebastopol Creek, Windham and Yea River.

Alexander (Alec) and Patricia (Pat) McGregor were unable to have children of their own, but were extremely dedicated to the community. Their input went above and beyond the normal assistance offered by other community members and volunteers. Both Alec and Pat are the only life members of the Junior Football Club (of which the reserve is home to), and they have been heavily involved in all community groups over their respective lives. Pat had also been the local kindergarten assistant for over 30 years, and they were both well known and adored in the community. The couple bequeathed a large amount of money to all of these groups. The name change is in their honour as thanks for all of their generosity.
